00:23:32.329 --> 00:23:34.120
And I would just love
to hear what more you

00:23:34.120 --> 00:23:35.990
have to say about that.

00:23:35.990 --> 00:23:37.540
CARMEN MARIA MACHADO: Yeah.

00:23:37.540 --> 00:23:38.970
So did anyone here
ever read book

00:23:38.970 --> 00:23:40.960
"The Scary Stories to
Tell in the Dark" books?

00:23:40.960 --> 00:23:41.459
OK.

00:23:41.459 --> 00:23:44.290
So if you've read my book or
if you haven't, "The Husband

00:23:44.290 --> 00:23:47.409
Stitch" is a retelling of a
story that actually is not

00:23:47.409 --> 00:23:47.950
in that book.

00:23:47.950 --> 00:23:48.750
People think it is.

00:23:48.750 --> 00:23:50.502
It's like a weird false memory.

00:23:50.502 --> 00:23:52.210
So Alvin Schwartz,
who wrote those books,

00:23:52.210 --> 00:23:54.569
also had another book called
"In a Dark, Dark Room"

00:23:54.569 --> 00:23:56.860
that was actually for younger
readers-- like not teens,

00:23:56.860 --> 00:23:59.844
but it was I Can
Read book that was

00:23:59.844 --> 00:24:01.510
like equally scary
stories with slightly

00:24:01.510 --> 00:24:03.280
less horrifying illustrations.

00:24:03.280 --> 00:24:05.749
And there was a story called
"The Green Ribbon" in there,

00:24:05.749 --> 00:24:07.540
about a girl with a
ribbon around her neck.

00:24:07.540 --> 00:24:09.310
And her husband is always
asking her about it,

00:24:09.310 --> 00:24:11.890
and she won't talk to him about
it, and then on her deathbed

00:24:11.890 --> 00:24:13.390
he unties it and
her head falls off.

00:24:16.237 --> 00:24:18.070
And I wanted to do a
retelling of the story,

00:24:18.070 --> 00:24:19.653
and the first story
in this colleciton

00:24:19.653 --> 00:24:20.770
is a retelling of that.

00:24:20.770 --> 00:24:23.505
It's sort of an urban legend.

00:24:23.505 --> 00:24:25.410
And in the Alvin Schwartz
scary stories book,

00:24:25.410 --> 00:24:26.770
there was a lot of
stage directions.

00:24:26.770 --> 00:24:28.780
Because the stories are meant
to be-- they're folk tales.

00:24:28.780 --> 00:24:30.280
They're meant to be performed.

00:24:30.280 --> 00:24:32.440
And so when I was a kid,
I was in Girl Scouts

00:24:32.440 --> 00:24:36.610
and I did a lot of camping,
and we would tell stories.

00:24:36.610 --> 00:24:39.190
And I learned really
quickly that this book

00:24:39.190 --> 00:24:41.590
was a great way of freaking
out my fellow Girl Scouts.

00:24:41.590 --> 00:24:43.560
And I could read the
story, and then there'd

00:24:43.560 --> 00:24:47.380
be a command at the end,
like who has my liver?

00:24:47.380 --> 00:24:48.130
Like that story.

00:24:48.130 --> 00:24:50.930
And then it would say, like,
grab the person next to you

00:24:50.930 --> 00:24:52.240
and be like, you have it!

00:24:52.240 --> 00:24:54.781
And I did and it made my fellow
Girl Scouts cry hysterically,

00:24:54.781 --> 00:24:57.760
and I was super into it because
people were having a reaction.

00:24:57.760 --> 00:25:00.670
Anyway, so I was really into the
idea of having stage directions

00:25:00.670 --> 00:25:01.240
in my story.

00:25:01.240 --> 00:25:03.656
But of course, I didn't want
them to be like regular stage

00:25:03.656 --> 00:25:04.300
directions.

00:25:04.300 --> 00:25:06.899
I wanted them to sort
of have some quality

00:25:06.899 --> 00:25:08.440
that reflected the
themes of the book

00:25:08.440 --> 00:25:10.104
or what I wanted to talk about.

00:25:10.104 --> 00:25:11.770
So in the opening
section of that story,

00:25:11.770 --> 00:25:12.722
I'm sort of saying--

00:25:12.722 --> 00:25:14.430
because in the actual
scary stories book,

00:25:14.430 --> 00:25:17.190
they'd be like, if you
read this story loud

00:25:17.190 --> 00:25:19.210
uss a squeaky voice
or a booming voice,

00:25:19.210 --> 00:25:20.920
or whatever sort of
reflects whatever

00:25:20.920 --> 00:25:23.080
the character's supposed to be.

00:25:23.080 --> 00:25:27.070
And I sort of wanted to make
a little nod to my experience

00:25:27.070 --> 00:25:29.710
as a person who
consumes a lot of media.

00:25:29.710 --> 00:25:30.530
I love TV.

00:25:30.530 --> 00:25:31.180
I love films.

00:25:31.180 --> 00:25:33.638
But a thing that frustrates
me, especially in genres that I

00:25:33.638 --> 00:25:36.437
love-- which is science
fiction and horror--

00:25:36.437 --> 00:25:38.770
is that female characters are
often very interchangeable

00:25:38.770 --> 00:25:41.170
and completely unmemorable.

00:25:41.170 --> 00:25:44.500
And so I wanted her to be
sort of slightly referring

00:25:44.500 --> 00:25:46.060
to the fact that
we sort of think

00:25:46.060 --> 00:25:48.202
of these female
characters like each

00:25:48.202 --> 00:25:50.410
of the women being described
in that opening section.

00:25:50.410 --> 00:25:52.618
It's like the men have these
very distinctive voices,

00:25:52.618 --> 00:25:55.000
and then the women are all
sort of interchangeable.

00:25:55.000 --> 00:25:57.541
The irony being that when I read
it aloud, it's me reading it

00:25:57.541 --> 00:26:00.450
and it's all the
same voice, right?

00:26:00.450 --> 00:26:03.070
But yeah, so I think it
was something I had to do,

00:26:03.070 --> 00:26:05.290
which is take a formal
constraint or a formal conceit

00:26:05.290 --> 00:26:08.350
in my work and use
it to just create

00:26:08.350 --> 00:26:09.940
some kind of narrative energy.

00:26:09.940 --> 00:26:13.610
And in that case, making
a point about a thing

00:26:13.610 --> 00:26:18.020
I have a thought about
about women in media.

00:26:18.020 --> 00:26:18.605
Yeah.

