00:32:24.630 --> 00:32:26.630
where the president and
Leo were standing there,

00:32:26.630 --> 00:32:27.245
and they're our heroes.

00:32:27.245 --> 00:32:28.310
They're like the
heroes of heroes,

00:32:28.310 --> 00:32:30.260
the top of the cream of
the crop of the people,

00:32:30.260 --> 00:32:32.384
and they're saying, they're
going, boys, the things

00:32:32.384 --> 00:32:33.482
we do to women.

00:32:33.482 --> 00:32:34.940
And they're sort
of acknowledging--

00:32:34.940 --> 00:32:37.170
like, a lot of your stories
are the other side of it,

00:32:37.170 --> 00:32:39.150
like yeah, these are the
frickin' things we do to women.

00:32:39.150 --> 00:32:41.420
And hearing it from the
males, they'll be like, yup.

00:32:41.420 --> 00:32:43.419
And then they go and say
something inappropriate

00:32:43.419 --> 00:32:44.930
to a woman.

00:32:44.930 --> 00:32:46.910
So I totally agree that
you can't separate--

00:32:46.910 --> 00:32:49.070
like, it is hard for me
to listen to Aaron Sorkin

00:32:49.070 --> 00:32:50.980
and be like, man, you're
brilliant but why can you--

00:32:50.980 --> 00:32:52.430
you have one strong
female character,

00:32:52.430 --> 00:32:54.050
and you're constantly sexually
harassing her on the screen.

00:32:54.050 --> 00:32:56.250
Like what the-- what
is wrong with you?

00:32:56.250 --> 00:32:59.535
I'm curious how your work, being
such the opposite perspective

00:32:59.535 --> 00:33:01.160
and being so strong
voiced in that way,

00:33:01.160 --> 00:33:03.710
like how have you found it
has impacted other people

00:33:03.710 --> 00:33:06.600
and impacted the literary
world that you live in?

00:33:06.600 --> 00:33:09.320
CARMEN MARIA MACHADO: Yeah, "The
West Wing" does not age well.

00:33:09.320 --> 00:33:11.640
I've also discovered this.

00:33:11.640 --> 00:33:12.290
It is true.

00:33:15.410 --> 00:33:19.600
Yeah, the sort of idea--

00:33:19.600 --> 00:33:22.030
I think what's been
really hard, again,

00:33:22.030 --> 00:33:25.240
as a person who consumes media--

00:33:25.240 --> 00:33:27.790
like, the media that I'm
most interested in absolutely

00:33:27.790 --> 00:33:29.350
not made for me.

00:33:29.350 --> 00:33:32.920
The genres I'm interested in are
genres where my demographic is

00:33:32.920 --> 00:33:34.390
an utter afterthought, right?

00:33:34.390 --> 00:33:38.540
And so that sort
of idea of, wow,

00:33:38.540 --> 00:33:41.967
I'm not even being considered
in any way in anything

00:33:41.967 --> 00:33:43.550
about this-- even
artists that I love.

00:33:43.550 --> 00:33:44.720
I like Aaron Sorkin.

00:33:44.720 --> 00:33:46.760
I love Joss Whedon.

00:33:46.760 --> 00:33:49.029
Lars Von Trier is a
filmmaker who I adore,

00:33:49.029 --> 00:33:50.570
even though like
literally every film

00:33:50.570 --> 00:33:53.720
is him taking a woman apart
on the screen for three hours,

00:33:53.720 --> 00:33:58.060
and that's like his entire
project over and over again.

00:33:58.060 --> 00:33:59.960
And it's really
hard, because those

00:33:59.960 --> 00:34:02.150
are artists that mean
a lot to me, whose

00:34:02.150 --> 00:34:03.314
work has meant a lot to me.

00:34:03.314 --> 00:34:04.730
"Buffy" is really
important to me.

00:34:07.401 --> 00:34:09.650
So at some point, I had to
come to this sense of peace

00:34:09.650 --> 00:34:12.959
where it's like, OK,
the art that I most--

00:34:12.959 --> 00:34:15.500
not all the art that I love,
but a lot of the art that I love

00:34:15.500 --> 00:34:19.550
is absolutely not made with
me in mind, and also at times

00:34:19.550 --> 00:34:26.150
is actively destructive
in certain ways

00:34:26.150 --> 00:34:29.030
and is very harmful
to women, for example,

00:34:29.030 --> 00:34:32.710
or people of color or
queer people or whoever.

00:34:32.710 --> 00:34:36.710
And so that's been a thing
I had come to terms with.

00:34:36.710 --> 00:34:38.239
But in terms of my own book--

00:34:38.239 --> 00:34:43.034
I mean, I'm really lucky because
the work that I write is--

00:34:43.034 --> 00:34:44.659
I was like, I want
to write a book that

00:34:44.659 --> 00:34:47.179
has all-female protagonists.

00:34:47.179 --> 00:34:48.860
Most of them are queer.

00:34:48.860 --> 00:34:50.600
I want lots of sex.

00:34:50.600 --> 00:34:54.067
I want weird genre stuff that
doesn't really have a category.

00:34:54.067 --> 00:34:55.650
I want all these
things for this book.

00:34:55.650 --> 00:34:57.470
And I was really
lucky that I just

00:34:57.470 --> 00:34:59.450
managed to find a
publisher who kind of got

00:34:59.450 --> 00:35:02.530
the vision of that project,
because I feel like--

00:35:02.530 --> 00:35:05.380
I mean, I once had a story
rejected by an editor.

00:35:05.380 --> 00:35:07.130
He gave me this content
where he was like,

00:35:07.130 --> 00:35:08.761
there's just no
men in this story.

00:35:08.761 --> 00:35:09.385
There are none.

00:35:09.385 --> 00:35:10.850
And I said, I know.

00:35:10.850 --> 00:35:12.490
I know there are none.

00:35:12.490 --> 00:35:13.580
It's about a mother.

00:35:13.580 --> 00:35:15.065
She's got sisters.

00:35:15.065 --> 00:35:16.190
Like, there was just like--

00:35:16.190 --> 00:35:17.690
I was like, I don't--
there's just--

00:35:17.690 --> 00:35:19.029
I mean, they just don't--

00:35:19.029 --> 00:35:20.695
because it would at
least get mentioned.

00:35:20.695 --> 00:35:22.100
They would mention the father.

00:35:22.100 --> 00:35:23.850
And I was like, why?

00:35:23.850 --> 00:35:28.130
And I feel like that sort
of reversal of perspective

00:35:28.130 --> 00:35:29.930
is intense.

00:35:29.930 --> 00:35:31.440
It's intense
[INAUDIBLE] deal with.

00:35:31.440 --> 00:35:33.273
And I think the reason
people respond really

00:35:33.273 --> 00:35:36.000
strongly to my book is
this sense of utter relief

00:35:36.000 --> 00:35:38.810
that that is being
sort of inverted,

00:35:38.810 --> 00:35:41.270
because we're just so used
to seeing the opposite.

00:35:41.270 --> 00:35:45.230
And so in that same way
that I'm also queer,

00:35:45.230 --> 00:35:47.030
and whenever I see a
queer character on TV

00:35:47.030 --> 00:35:50.330
or hear a song that could be
thought about as a queer song,

00:35:50.330 --> 00:35:51.260
I'm just all over it.

00:35:51.260 --> 00:35:52.370
I'm like, I will
give it all my money.

00:35:52.370 --> 00:35:52.970
I will watch it.

00:35:52.970 --> 00:35:53.678
I will follow it.

00:35:53.678 --> 00:35:55.890
Because I'm seeing this teeny--

00:35:55.890 --> 00:35:56.940
whoops, sorry.

00:35:56.940 --> 00:35:58.670
I'm seeing this
tiny place where I

00:35:58.670 --> 00:36:01.120
feel even slightly represented.

00:36:01.120 --> 00:36:02.620
Or like "Jane the
Virgin" is a show.

00:36:02.620 --> 00:36:05.120
I Like, how many liquids
can you see on TV?

00:36:05.120 --> 00:36:11.009
So when I see that, I respond
to it really strongly.

00:36:11.009 --> 00:36:12.800
And I feel like people
are feeling that way

00:36:12.800 --> 00:36:13.910
about my book,
where they're like,

00:36:13.910 --> 00:36:15.860
I'm seeing a thing that
I didn't see before.

00:36:15.860 --> 00:36:16.620
I'm hungry for it.

00:36:16.620 --> 00:36:17.720
I didn't even know
how hungry I was.

00:36:17.720 --> 00:36:20.150
Or maybe you did know how
angry you were, but seeing it

00:36:20.150 --> 00:36:22.190
is this really exciting thing.

00:36:22.190 --> 00:36:23.450
So the response to my book--

00:36:23.450 --> 00:36:25.209
and honestly, I
think the political--

00:36:25.209 --> 00:36:27.500
even though I've been writing
this book for five years.

00:36:27.500 --> 00:36:29.784
Women's lives have
always been garbage.

00:36:29.784 --> 00:36:30.950
They continue to be garbage.

00:36:30.950 --> 00:36:33.680
But right now it's
particularly bad.

00:36:33.680 --> 00:36:35.151
But we're in this
political moment

00:36:35.151 --> 00:36:37.400
where suddenly my book is
like extra weirdly relevant,

00:36:37.400 --> 00:36:39.050
even though that sucks.

00:36:39.050 --> 00:36:40.160
I wish it wasn't.

00:36:40.160 --> 00:36:42.074
I wish it was less relevant.

00:36:42.074 --> 00:36:43.490
But yes, I think
that's why people

00:36:43.490 --> 00:36:46.436
are responding so strongly to
the book, is because of this.

00:36:46.436 --> 00:36:47.810
Because not only
are people like,

00:36:47.810 --> 00:36:49.518
that's familiar to me
from my whole life,

00:36:49.518 --> 00:36:52.880
but also in terms of
just what's happening

00:36:52.880 --> 00:36:56.750
right now politically.

00:36:56.750 --> 00:37:00.160
AUDIENCE: I just want
follow up a little bit.

00:37:00.160 --> 00:37:06.850
I'm curious about how you
think about the line between,

00:37:06.850 --> 00:37:10.700
here are the stories that
I've published so far

00:37:10.700 --> 00:37:16.160
and a book as a thing that sort
of exists in and of itself.

00:37:16.160 --> 00:37:20.970
What was the process like
of putting it together

00:37:20.970 --> 00:37:22.156
as a whole package?

00:37:22.156 --> 00:37:23.280
CARMEN MARIA MACHADO: Sure.

00:37:23.280 --> 00:37:25.775
I see you have the short
story advent calendar.

00:37:25.775 --> 00:37:26.400
AUDIENCE: I do.

00:37:26.400 --> 00:37:27.525
CARMEN MARIA MACHADO: Yeah.

00:37:27.525 --> 00:37:29.000
[LAUGHING]

00:37:29.000 --> 00:37:34.350
Yeah, so I've been publishing
fiction for five, six years now

00:37:34.350 --> 00:37:34.975
professionally.

00:37:34.975 --> 00:37:37.474
And I've published a lot more
stories than are in this book.

00:37:37.474 --> 00:37:39.594
There are only eight
stories in this book.

00:37:39.594 --> 00:37:41.010
And it's weird,
because when I was

00:37:41.010 --> 00:37:43.200
sort of talking to editors
in the process of trying

00:37:43.200 --> 00:37:45.540
to publish it, there was someone
who was sort of interested

00:37:45.540 --> 00:37:46.770
and was saying,
well, I feel like you

00:37:46.770 --> 00:37:48.144
could add all
these other stories

00:37:48.144 --> 00:37:51.500
that I know you've published
but aren't in this version

00:37:51.500 --> 00:37:53.142
of the book.

00:37:53.142 --> 00:37:55.350
And I feel there's two
philosophies about short story

00:37:55.350 --> 00:37:57.030
collections.

00:37:57.030 --> 00:37:59.250
A short story collection
is like the last 15

00:37:59.250 --> 00:38:01.833
stories you've published, or the
last 10 stories you published

00:38:01.833 --> 00:38:06.060
or whatever, or it has
a strong thematic heart

00:38:06.060 --> 00:38:08.400
and a strong thematic link.

00:38:08.400 --> 00:38:11.000
And for me, when I read
short story collections

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:12.055
I prefer the latter.

00:38:12.055 --> 00:38:13.680
I don't like a bunch
of random stories.

00:38:13.680 --> 00:38:15.679
I want them to feel like
they're in conversation

00:38:15.679 --> 00:38:17.450
with each other
in some capacity.

00:38:17.450 --> 00:38:21.800
So when I was in grad
school, I published my--

00:38:21.800 --> 00:38:24.486
my thesis, which had the
same title as this book,

00:38:24.486 --> 00:38:26.360
only had three common
stories with this book.

00:38:26.360 --> 00:38:27.776
And there's a lot
of other stories

00:38:27.776 --> 00:38:30.070
that are since retired
in the Disney vault.

00:38:30.070 --> 00:38:34.190
I've tied them away and
no one will ever see them.

00:38:34.190 --> 00:38:39.150
But I wanted-- because
I sort of realized, wow,

00:38:39.150 --> 00:38:41.970
some of the stories I really
like, and other stories--

00:38:41.970 --> 00:38:44.716
it's not that I don't
like them, or they're

00:38:44.716 --> 00:38:45.590
about something else.

00:38:45.590 --> 00:38:49.490
Like, they're not about
women's bodies and sex.

00:38:49.490 --> 00:38:51.710
There were themes that
I had for this book

00:38:51.710 --> 00:38:53.740
that I wanted the
stories to be a part of.

00:38:53.740 --> 00:38:56.944
And if they fell outside those
parameters, I was like, well,

00:38:56.944 --> 00:38:57.860
it's for another book.

00:38:57.860 --> 00:38:59.360
Or maybe it's a
one-off story that's

00:38:59.360 --> 00:39:01.024
not going to go in a book.

00:39:01.024 --> 00:39:02.690
And what's really
interesting about that

00:39:02.690 --> 00:39:06.110
is as I was wrapping
this book up,

00:39:06.110 --> 00:39:08.270
I sort of was writing
brand new stories

00:39:08.270 --> 00:39:12.020
and was realizing like, oh wow,
I have a second book in me.

00:39:12.020 --> 00:39:14.540
I have another set
of interests that

00:39:14.540 --> 00:39:17.780
is related to these
stories in certain ways,

00:39:17.780 --> 00:39:20.510
like still lots of sex,
still queer women, et cetera.

00:39:20.510 --> 00:39:22.220
But I have different interests.

00:39:22.220 --> 00:39:25.520
I'm writing this book now where
memory is a central theme.

00:39:25.520 --> 00:39:27.650
And that's not really a
theme that exists in here,

00:39:27.650 --> 00:39:29.396
but it's this new
idea that I'm having.

00:39:29.396 --> 00:39:30.895
And so it was
actually pretty cool--

00:39:30.895 --> 00:39:33.214
because I feel like
when you're trying

00:39:33.214 --> 00:39:35.630
to put together a debut book,
it's like that's your focus.

00:39:35.630 --> 00:39:37.580
You're like, this is my book.

00:39:37.580 --> 00:39:39.300
This is a thing in my brain.

00:39:39.300 --> 00:39:40.841
And then you have
it and you're like,

00:39:40.841 --> 00:39:44.060
oh, I have other books in
my brain about other things.

00:39:44.060 --> 00:39:45.880
And it's a very odd
feeling when you've

00:39:45.880 --> 00:39:46.940
been really focused
on publishing

00:39:46.940 --> 00:39:48.170
a book for your whole life.

00:39:50.880 --> 00:39:52.730
So now I new projects.

00:39:52.730 --> 00:39:57.650
And these stories just get--
my editor really wanted

00:39:57.650 --> 00:39:59.439
a tight, lean collection.

00:39:59.439 --> 00:40:00.980
Two of these stories
are really huge.

00:40:00.980 --> 00:40:05.840
"The Resident" and "Especially
Heinous" are massive.

00:40:05.840 --> 00:40:07.970
And so yeah, so it ended
up being two novellas,

00:40:07.970 --> 00:40:10.100
six short stories.

00:40:10.100 --> 00:40:12.957
It's a fairly
average-sized collection.

00:40:12.957 --> 00:40:15.290
Yeah, and I just didn't want
to add anything else to it.

00:40:15.290 --> 00:40:17.870
And these felt like they
were very tight, and sort of

00:40:17.870 --> 00:40:19.857
in conversation with each other.

00:40:19.857 --> 00:40:20.690
So yeah, that's why.

00:40:20.690 --> 00:40:23.030
But I really like the
result. I feel like this

00:40:23.030 --> 00:40:24.721
was the book I needed it to be.

00:40:24.721 --> 00:40:26.720
I'm glad I didn't publish
earlier versions of it

00:40:26.720 --> 00:40:28.880
with more stories that
weren't as connected.

00:40:32.030 --> 00:40:34.820
AUDIENCE: So I was curious
when for you or what

00:40:34.820 --> 00:40:37.790
was the book when you
first felt like you

00:40:37.790 --> 00:40:39.659
saw yourself represented?

00:40:39.659 --> 00:40:41.450
CARMEN MARIA MACHADO:
Oh, like that I read?

00:40:41.450 --> 00:40:42.210
AUDIENCE: That you read, yeah.

00:40:42.210 --> 00:40:43.790
And when that
happened in your life,

00:40:43.790 --> 00:40:45.883
and how long it took
for that to happen.

00:40:45.883 --> 00:40:47.940
For me, it took until
I was a teenager.

00:40:47.940 --> 00:40:49.430
CARMEN MARIA MACHADO: Yeah.

00:40:49.430 --> 00:40:52.370
Yeah, I mean-- there have
been bits and spurts sort

00:40:52.370 --> 00:40:53.380
of throughout.

00:40:53.380 --> 00:40:55.160
I was a voracious
reader as a teen.

00:40:55.160 --> 00:40:57.710
I read a lot of books--

00:40:57.710 --> 00:40:59.660
I mean, books like--

00:40:59.660 --> 00:41:01.370
I read, like, "Animorphs."

00:41:01.370 --> 00:41:02.450
I read all those.

00:41:02.450 --> 00:41:05.000
I mean, I read a lot of series.

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:06.830
But I really loved
"Wrinkle in Time."

00:41:06.830 --> 00:41:09.410
That was a really
formative book for me.

00:41:12.939 --> 00:41:14.480
I mean, I didn't
really get to read--

00:41:14.480 --> 00:41:16.020
I grew up in the '90s, so
I wasn't really reading

00:41:16.020 --> 00:41:17.570
many books about queer teens.

00:41:17.570 --> 00:41:19.925
But in terms of
female voices, there

00:41:19.925 --> 00:41:21.300
was like "Behind
the Attic Wall,"

00:41:21.300 --> 00:41:23.010
which was a novel that was
really important to me.

00:41:23.010 --> 00:41:23.760
You know it!

00:41:23.760 --> 00:41:24.870
You know it!

00:41:24.870 --> 00:41:26.030
It's so good.

00:41:26.030 --> 00:41:26.790
Yes, it's so good.

00:41:26.790 --> 00:41:29.222
OK, we could talk it after,
because it's so good.

00:41:29.222 --> 00:41:30.930
And whenever I say to
people who know it,

00:41:30.930 --> 00:41:32.220
they get incredibly excited.

00:41:32.220 --> 00:41:33.150
It's such a good book.

00:41:33.150 --> 00:41:37.100
So that was a really formative
book for me, where I--

00:41:37.100 --> 00:41:39.780
I mean, every teenager and
every pre-teen is like, oh,

00:41:39.780 --> 00:41:40.864
I'm so gawky and awkward.

00:41:40.864 --> 00:41:41.530
No one likes me.

00:41:41.530 --> 00:41:44.790
So it's easy to identify
with a character in a book,

00:41:44.790 --> 00:41:47.819
because they're all
like gawky and--

00:41:47.819 --> 00:41:49.860
they're like, oh, I have
problems making friends.

00:41:49.860 --> 00:41:51.810
It's like, yeah, we all do.

00:41:51.810 --> 00:41:53.700
Welcome to the club.

00:41:53.700 --> 00:41:54.200
Yeah.

00:41:54.200 --> 00:41:56.300
And then as I got older--

00:41:56.300 --> 00:42:00.110
the work that sort
of really kicked off

00:42:00.110 --> 00:42:02.410
what I say is sort
of my voice, or where

00:42:02.410 --> 00:42:05.480
I felt like I was
reading work that I

00:42:05.480 --> 00:42:07.550
wanted to respond to
with my own work, which

00:42:07.550 --> 00:42:09.470
was a very distinct sort
of moment in my life.

00:42:09.470 --> 00:42:12.050
I was reading people like
Kelly Link, Karen Russell,

00:42:12.050 --> 00:42:15.740
Helen Oyeyemi, George Saunders.

00:42:15.740 --> 00:42:19.250
Mostly female writers.

00:42:19.250 --> 00:42:22.880
And yeah, it was like short
stories and weird stuff,

00:42:22.880 --> 00:42:26.510
and just like felt weird and
had a lot of women in them

00:42:26.510 --> 00:42:28.670
and were just really
weird and interesting.

00:42:28.670 --> 00:42:31.730
So I feel like there were
sort of multiple steps.

00:42:31.730 --> 00:42:33.300
And then also like
in high school,

00:42:33.300 --> 00:42:37.040
I had this teacher who gave me--

00:42:37.040 --> 00:42:39.107
it was public school,
so we were constantly

00:42:39.107 --> 00:42:40.190
learning, like, Hemingway.

00:42:40.190 --> 00:42:43.520
And I really, really hate
Hemingway still to this day.

00:42:43.520 --> 00:42:46.130
And I would just
yell at every class--

00:42:46.130 --> 00:42:47.747
poor Mrs. [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:47.747 --> 00:42:50.330
Every class, she'd be like let's
talk about-- and I'd be like,

00:42:50.330 --> 00:42:51.625
he's an alcoholic.

00:42:51.625 --> 00:42:52.250
I had thoughts.

00:42:52.250 --> 00:42:54.920
I was like, he's
horrible to women.

00:42:54.920 --> 00:42:57.270
I hate everything
happening-- oh my gosh,

00:42:57.270 --> 00:43:01.030
I pulled my mic down in
my rage of Hemingway.

00:43:01.030 --> 00:43:03.400
And I was really mad, and
she stopped calling on me

00:43:03.400 --> 00:43:04.234
for awhile.

00:43:04.234 --> 00:43:05.900
My hand would be like
seriously raising,

00:43:05.900 --> 00:43:07.566
and she'd be like,
Carmen, I didn't even

00:43:07.566 --> 00:43:10.430
want to hear what you have to
say about Ernest Hemingway.

00:43:10.430 --> 00:43:12.977
But she could tell that
I was frustrated by what

00:43:12.977 --> 00:43:14.060
we were reading in school.

00:43:14.060 --> 00:43:17.420
And we only ever read like one
book by a woman my entire--

00:43:17.420 --> 00:43:19.990
we read "Jane Eyre"
and that was like it,

00:43:19.990 --> 00:43:21.380
and then everything
else was men.

00:43:21.380 --> 00:43:26.057
So I was very frustrated, even
though I loved English class.

00:43:26.057 --> 00:43:28.640
And so one day, my teacher Mrs.
[INAUDIBLE],, bless her heart,

00:43:28.640 --> 00:43:31.550
came in with a pile of books
from her personal library

00:43:31.550 --> 00:43:33.300
and she said, I think
you will like these.

00:43:33.300 --> 00:43:34.050
You need to read them.

00:43:34.050 --> 00:43:35.800
And it was "One Hundred
Years of Solitude"

00:43:35.800 --> 00:43:41.510
by Gabriel Garcia Marquez,
Gloria Naylor's "Mama Day,"

00:43:41.510 --> 00:43:48.110
Henry James' "What Maisie Knew,"
Kate Chopin's "The Awakening,"

00:43:48.110 --> 00:43:49.600
and a handful of others.

00:43:49.600 --> 00:43:53.930
And I suddenly was
also able to just see

00:43:53.930 --> 00:43:55.597
what was possible in
literature and what

00:43:55.597 --> 00:43:57.721
it was like to write from
all the different places.

00:43:57.721 --> 00:43:58.710
And like, I don't know.

00:43:58.710 --> 00:44:00.210
I just really-- so
I feel like I had

00:44:00.210 --> 00:44:03.470
these stages of self-discovery
as a young person

00:44:03.470 --> 00:44:05.990
because of what I was reading,
this very directed thing

00:44:05.990 --> 00:44:08.150
to happen to me
like in high school,

00:44:08.150 --> 00:44:10.700
and then when I was in grad
school I had a lot of friends

00:44:10.700 --> 00:44:13.580
who were sort of like, you
need to be reading these people

00:44:13.580 --> 00:44:15.810
because that's what you want
to be doing as a writer.

00:44:15.810 --> 00:44:17.810
And then I felt like my
mind was like blown open

00:44:17.810 --> 00:44:20.350
and I was like, oh my god,
everything is amazing.

00:44:20.350 --> 00:44:21.700
Literature!

00:44:21.700 --> 00:44:22.760
It was just so exciting.

00:44:22.760 --> 00:44:24.343
So I think it's been
different phases.

00:44:28.004 --> 00:44:29.420
AUDIENCE: You
talked about the way

00:44:29.420 --> 00:44:31.620
that the stories
here go together.

00:44:31.620 --> 00:44:34.430
And I wonder if you'd talk
about the name a little,

00:44:34.430 --> 00:44:36.604
"Her Body and Other Parties."

00:44:36.604 --> 00:44:38.270
You mentioned "Jane
the Virgin" earlier.

00:44:38.270 --> 00:44:43.440
I feel like there's this group
of subversive and thoughtful

00:44:43.440 --> 00:44:45.540
media with this sort
of like, yeah, I

00:44:45.540 --> 00:44:46.790
know you think of me meme.

00:44:46.790 --> 00:44:47.540
"Jane the Virgin."

00:44:47.540 --> 00:44:50.926
"Crazy Ex Girlfriend," yeah.

00:44:50.926 --> 00:44:52.900
I wondered if you'd talk
about that a little.

00:44:52.900 --> 00:44:55.150
CARMEN MARIA MACHADO: That's
a great question, and one

00:44:55.150 --> 00:44:57.270
that I have a lot
of thoughts about.

00:44:57.270 --> 00:44:58.472
Yeah, I really-- it's funny.

00:44:58.472 --> 00:45:00.930
I actually did not watch "Crazy
Ex Girlfriend" for a while,

00:45:00.930 --> 00:45:02.830
because the title was
so off-putting to me.

00:45:02.830 --> 00:45:05.564
And then something who knows
me was like, no, no, no.

00:45:05.564 --> 00:45:06.730
You really need to watch it.

00:45:06.730 --> 00:45:07.320
You will love it.

00:45:07.320 --> 00:45:09.690
And I did, and I think it's one
of the best shows on television

00:45:09.690 --> 00:45:10.190
right now.

00:45:10.190 --> 00:45:11.070
I absolutely love it.

00:45:11.070 --> 00:45:13.380
"Jane the Virgin"
also, I was like,

00:45:13.380 --> 00:45:15.390
what a weird title for a show.

00:45:15.390 --> 00:45:19.150
But yeah, I mean, this
story collection--

00:45:19.150 --> 00:45:20.260
there's a few reasons.

00:45:20.260 --> 00:45:22.335
So I wanted--

00:45:24.846 --> 00:45:28.290
I asked a friend, how do people
name short story collections?

00:45:28.290 --> 00:45:30.210
And he was like,
well, oftentimes

00:45:30.210 --> 00:45:32.010
it's the title of
one of the stories,

00:45:32.010 --> 00:45:33.690
but it's a title
that sort of embodies

00:45:33.690 --> 00:45:36.589
the themes of the whole book.

00:45:36.589 --> 00:45:38.130
If you read a short
story collection,

00:45:38.130 --> 00:45:39.780
you'll notice that
usually the title is

00:45:39.780 --> 00:45:41.970
a title of one of the stories.

00:45:41.970 --> 00:45:44.760
But none of the titles
were working for me

00:45:44.760 --> 00:45:45.630
in that capacity.

00:45:45.630 --> 00:45:46.963
I was looking at all the titles.

00:45:46.963 --> 00:45:49.287
I was like, none of these
feel like a book title.

00:45:49.287 --> 00:45:50.370
But I love titling things.

00:45:50.370 --> 00:45:54.212
It's like a weird hobby I have.

00:45:54.212 --> 00:45:55.920
So yeah, I was sort
of thinking about it.

00:45:55.920 --> 00:45:58.824
And then I also was
thinking about this book

00:45:58.824 --> 00:46:00.990
that I really love, Ted
Chiang's "Story of Your Life

00:46:00.990 --> 00:46:04.044
and Others," which is a book
which if you haven't read,

00:46:04.044 --> 00:46:06.210
you absolutely must, because
it is literally perfect

00:46:06.210 --> 00:46:07.335
and Ted Chiang is a genius.

00:46:07.335 --> 00:46:11.673
It's science fiction, and
it's gorgeous and amazing.

00:46:11.673 --> 00:46:13.415
So that title has
that sort of pun,

00:46:13.415 --> 00:46:15.040
where it's like
"Stories of Your Life,"

00:46:15.040 --> 00:46:16.710
which is the name of
one of his stories,

00:46:16.710 --> 00:46:18.751
"and others," which can
be like "and other lives"

00:46:18.751 --> 00:46:19.860
or "and other stories."

00:46:19.860 --> 00:46:23.550
So using that sort of structure
of "and other stories,"

00:46:23.550 --> 00:46:25.810
sort of riffing
on that structure.

00:46:25.810 --> 00:46:28.020
So then I had that in mind.

00:46:28.020 --> 00:46:29.940
And then I started mashing
my titles together.

00:46:29.940 --> 00:46:33.900
I was like, let's see what
key words from my story titles

00:46:33.900 --> 00:46:38.040
could be put together
in this structure.

00:46:38.040 --> 00:46:40.020
And I came up with--

00:46:40.020 --> 00:46:44.280
I think like "Bodies
and Other Parties,"

00:46:44.280 --> 00:46:46.000
because women have bodies.

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:47.159
That's in the title.

00:46:47.159 --> 00:46:49.200
And then I was, but I feel
like I want the gender

00:46:49.200 --> 00:46:50.030
element to be in there.

00:46:50.030 --> 00:46:51.321
So then I was like, "Her Body."

00:46:51.321 --> 00:46:52.470
"Her Body and Other."

00:46:52.470 --> 00:46:53.678
"Her Body and Other Parties."

00:46:53.678 --> 00:46:55.170
And I just really liked it.

00:46:55.170 --> 00:46:56.160
And then it just stuck.

00:46:56.160 --> 00:46:59.010
It's been the title of this
book even before this book

00:46:59.010 --> 00:47:00.774
even remotely looked like this.

00:47:00.774 --> 00:47:02.190
And I feel like
it also helped me,

00:47:02.190 --> 00:47:04.100
because it was something
to work toward--

00:47:04.100 --> 00:47:06.060
it was like a
lighthouse that I could

00:47:06.060 --> 00:47:11.160
sort of be moving toward with my
work and the way I do my edits.

00:47:11.160 --> 00:47:14.720
So yeah, that was just--

00:47:14.720 --> 00:47:17.052
I mean, that was just
how I kind of came to it.

00:47:17.052 --> 00:47:18.385
But titles are really important.

00:47:18.385 --> 00:47:20.630
And yeah, I do think that
sort of quality of like,

00:47:20.630 --> 00:47:22.460
fuck you for what you
think of me, right?

00:47:22.460 --> 00:47:24.200
That title is such a good--

00:47:24.200 --> 00:47:25.080
it's really fun.

00:47:25.080 --> 00:47:27.740
And I think that
level of subversion

00:47:27.740 --> 00:47:30.170
is really important
and really interesting,

00:47:30.170 --> 00:47:33.140
and I think that both those
examples that you gave

00:47:33.140 --> 00:47:38.330
are female-driven
properties, one of whom

00:47:38.330 --> 00:47:39.770
was a woman of color.

00:47:39.770 --> 00:47:41.270
I think that's
important, that sort

00:47:41.270 --> 00:47:44.060
of very, very self-aware title.

00:47:44.060 --> 00:47:45.610
So yeah.

00:47:45.610 --> 00:47:46.660
That's it.

00:47:46.660 --> 00:47:47.300
Yeah?

00:47:47.300 --> 00:47:49.133
All right, well thank
you so much, everyone.

00:47:49.133 --> 00:47:50.820
It was so lovely to talk to you.

00:47:50.820 --> 00:47:54.170
[APPLAUSE]

